Wash and dry all produce. Trim any stems from @green beans{12%oz}, then cut into 1-inch
pieces. Peel @ginger{1%thumb}, then mince until you have 2 TBSP. Mince or grate
@garlic{2%cloves}. Trim, then thinly slice @scallions{2%unit}, keeping greens and
whites separate. Trim, then thinly slice @button mushrooms{8%oz}.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{4%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Cut @chicken tenders{24%oz} into thin strips, then season all over with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Add to pan and cook until browned, about ~{2%minutes} per side.

> Work in batches to avoid overcrowding.

Remove from pan and set aside.

Heat another large drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add
@shredded carrots{8%oz}, mushrooms, and green beans. Cook, tossing, until softened,
~{5-7%minutes}. Add chicken, ginger, scallion whites, and garlic. Cook, tossing,
until ginger and garlic are fragrant, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and
pepper.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @soy sauce{2%tbsp}, @veggie stock concentrate{2%unit},
@hoisin sauce{2%tbsp}, @sugar{4%tsp}, and @water{1/2%cup}.

> We sent more hoisin sauce - use as desired.

Lower heat under pan to medium and stir in sauce. Let simmer until sauce is
slightly reduced, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add @udon noodles{16%oz} to pan and cook, tossing,
until tender, ~{3-4%minutes}. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

> If noodles seem stiff while cooking, add a splash of water to help loosen things up.

Divide lo mein between bowls. Garnish with @scallion greens{} and serve.